1 11. Sodium benzoate;
2 12. Sodium nitrate;
3 13. Titanium dioxide; and
4 14. Trichloroethylene.
5 C. 1. Upon the effective date of this act, no person, firm,
6 association, corporation, or any other entity shall manufacture,
7 compound, brew, distill, produce, process, sell, deliver,
8 distribute, hold, offer, or expose for sale as food additives or
9 food color additives or any other food product or additives or color
10 additives used to reformulate ingestible drugs that contain any of
11 the ingredients provided in subsections A and B of this section
12 without disclosing those ingredients on the product label, website,
13 or a quick response (QR) code on the product label linked to a
14 website.
15 2. No person, firm, association, corporation, or any other
16 entity shall be considered in compliance with this subsection unless
17 the product bears a label that states conspicuously a warning to the
18 consumer that the product contains one or more of the ingredients
19 provided in subsections A and B of this section. Such warning shall
20 display the following message: “WARNING. THIS PRODUCT CONTAINS
21 INGREDIENTS AND/OR CHEMICALS HAZARDOUS FOR INGESTION AND MAY CAUSE
22 ADVERSE HEALTH EFFECTS IN HUMANS.”
23 D. The State Board of Agriculture is authorized to issue a
24 written or printed “stop-sale” or “notice of violation” order to the
Req. No. 1884 Page 3

1 pers on, firm, association, corporation, or any other entity of a
2 product in violation of this section.
3 E. 1. The Oklahoma Department of Agriculture, Food, and
4 Forestry may take one or more of the following actions:
5 a. assess an administrative penalty pursuant to Section
6 2-18 of Title 2 of the Oklahoma Statutes for each day
7 of violation. Each day a violation continues shall be
8 a separate and distinct offense,
9 b. assess an administrative penalty of Five Thousand
10 Dollars ($5,000.00) for subsequent violations, or
11 c. bring an action for injunctive relief granted by a
12 district court.
13 2. A district court may grant injunctive relief to prevent a
14 violation of, or to compel compliance with, any of the provisions of
15 this section or any rule promulgated thereunder.
16 3. Nothing in this section shall preclude the Department from
17 seeking penalties in district court in the maximum amount allowed by
18 law. The assessment of penalties in an administrative enforcement
19 proceeding shall not prevent the subsequent assessment by a court of
20 the maximum criminal penalties for violations of this section.
21 4. Any person assessed an administrative penalty may be
22 required to pay, in addition to such penalty amount and interest
23 thereon, attorney fees and costs associated with the collection of
24 such penalties.
Req. No. 1884 Page 4

1 5. Any administrative penalty required to be paid pursuant to
2 the provisions of this subsection shall be deposited into the State
3 Department of Agriculture Revolving Fund. The expenditure of these
4 fines shall be limited to conducting the provisions of the Oklahoma
5 Farm to School Program Act.
6 F. The State Board of Agriculture shall promulgate rules
7 necessary to implement the provisions of this section.
8 SECTION 2. This act shall become effective November 1, 2025.
